 body of urban oral memory. In addition to this historical/literary interaction the book is a contribution to the historiography of southern African cities, bringing out the experiential and cultural dimensions, and combining black and white urban social history. TERENCE RANGER was Emeritus Rhodes Professor of Race Relations, University of Oxford and author of many books including Writing Revolt, Are we not also Men? (1995), Voices from the Rocks (1999) and was co-editor of Violence and Memory (2000). Zimbabwe: Weaver Press  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / African.2bisacsh  aAfrican cities.  aBulawayo Burning.  aButterfly Burning.  aRhodes Professor of Race Relations.  aSocial History.  aTERENCE RANGER.  aUniversity of Oxford.  aYvonne Vera.  aZimbabwean cultural life.  ablack and white urban social history.  acultural dimensions.  aexperiential.  ahistorical research.  ahistoriography.  aliterary imagination.  asouthern African cities.  aurban oral memory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615893340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158933/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles